title: Iowa Medical Board

communications.subject: Iowa Open Records Law Request: Iowa Medical Board
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Iowa Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. All physician disciplinary actions from 2019-2024 related to:
   - Mental health conditions
   - Substance use
   - Behavioral health issues

2. Comprehensive physician health program policies, specifically:
   - Approach classification: Punitive vs. Supportive measures
   - Detailed breakdown of intervention strategies
   - Resources allocated to physician wellness programs

3. Detailed statistics on:
   - Self-reported vs. discovered cases
   - Return to practice rates
   - Appeal outcomes
   - Comparative analysis of intervention effectiveness

4. Physician Health Program (PHP) evaluation documents:
   - Internal studies or reports on program effectiveness
   - Comparative analyses of intervention approaches
   - Confidentiality and support mechanisms

5. Professional Assistance Program details:
   - Formal and informal agreements with Iowa Medical Board
   - Confidentiality policies and their implementation
   - Reporting protocols (board reporting rates)
   - Physician outcome tracking
   - Long-term support and monitoring strategies

6. Comprehensive program assessments:
   - External and internal program audits
   - Cost-benefit analysis of support programs
   - Physician feedback and satisfaction metrics
   - Comparative analysis with other state approaches

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

communications.subject: RE: Iowa Open Records Law Request: Iowa Medical Board
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Stuecker and team,

Thank you for your thoughtful and prompt response to our open records request. We sincerely appreciate the data and links you provided, especially the self-report/referral breakdown and references to the Iowa Administrative Code and relevant statutes.

We understand the need for confidentiality in individual cases. However, we respectfully believe there may be a misunderstanding regarding the scope of Iowa Code §21.5(g). While this provision clearly protects specific case discussions or investigative matters, it does not appear to prohibit disclosure of general policies, administrative procedures, or contractual agreements that govern the operation of the Physician Health Program (PHP). Such documents are essential for public transparency and are not inherently protected merely by their association with a confidential program.

Because this issue is a central component of our national research into PHP structures and oversight, we kindly submit the following follow-up requests:

Any contracts or memoranda of understanding between the Iowa Medical Board and the Iowa PHP or any third-party entities managing physician monitoring, including the Professional Assistance Program.

These may be redacted as needed to protect names or private health information.

Meeting minutes from the Physician Health Committee (or equivalent) between 2019 and 2024, specifically those addressing program operations, procedural updates, or structural evaluations.

We are not seeking identifiable physician information and are happy to accept redacted copies if necessary.

Finally, we respectfully encourage your department to consider conducting or commissioning an internal audit or outcomes assessment of the program’s long-term effectiveness, including return-to-practice metrics, physician feedback, and support outcomes. We note that the absence of such data is common among many states, but also represents a gap in quality assurance that merits attention.

Thank you again for your time, cooperation, and ongoing commitment to public service. We look forward to your reply and will gladly work with your office to clarify any aspects of this request.

Warm regards,

title: FAFSA Updates

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FAFSA Updates
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All records related to the "2026-2027 Free Application for Federal Student Aid" update, including records sent to the Office of Management and Budget, inclusive of (but not necessarily limited to) OMB control number 1845-0001, Department of Education docket ED-2025-SCC-0011, and Federal Register doc 2025-02191.

The Department of Education has announced broad changes to the FAFSA (https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-education-announces-improvements-fafsar-form) but has not provided the public with the exact proposed changes. While it is my understanding the Paperwork Reduction Act does not necessarily require publishing changes sought from OMB, it is difficult, if not impossible, to making meaningful public comments to OMB about the proposed changes.

The Department of Education claims the proposed changes will decrease the public burden by OVER TWO MILLION HOURS. This is a substantial change. Therefore, I am requesting a fee waiver, as the Department of Education press release states, but does not specify, vague policy changes. It is in the public interest to understand these policy changes, how it may impact public burden under the Paperwork Reduction Act, and how other organizations who rely on the FAFSA, including state universities, will be affected by these changes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Karl Koscher

title: Dejene Mortality Review

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Dejene Mortality Review
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Serawit Gezahegn Dejene, (DOB: 3/29/79; COC: Ethiopia) who died January 29, 2025, following his detention at the Eloy Detention Center (EDC) in Eloy, Arizona, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddr-SerawitGezahegnDejene.pdf. 

I make this request as a member of the media, and therefore seek a fee waiver. Representative edited works based on prior FOIA requests like this one may be reviewed here: https://theappeal.org/authors/andrew-free/; and here: https://atlpresscollective.com/2025/01/31/new-record-sheds-light-on-unreported-death-in-atlanta-airport-customs-inspection/.

Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your 3/13/2025, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for all records pertaining to A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Serawit Gezahegn Dejene, (DOB: 3/29/79; COC: Ethiopia) who died January 29, 2025, following his detention at the Eloy Detention Center (EDC) in Eloy, Arizona, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddr-SerawitGezahegnDejene.pdf..  Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. 

We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison, Daniel Edgington at 500 12th Street, SW, Washington DC 20536 or (866) 633-1182. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-ICFO-25061. Please use this number in future correspondence.

Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025, your request for a waiver of all assessable FOIA fees, and your request for expedited treatment. Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. Specifically, you have requested all records pertaining to A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Serawit Gezahegn Dejene, (DOB: 3/29/79; COC: Ethiopia) who died January 29, 2025, following his detention at the Eloy Detention Center (EDC) in Eloy, Arizona, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddr-SerawitGezahegnDejene.pdf.. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Your request for expedited treatment is hereby denied. 

Under the DHS FOIA regulations, expedited processing of a FOIA request is warranted if the request involves “circumstances in which the lack of expedited treatment could reasonably be expected to pose an imminent threat to the life or physical safety of an individual,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1)(i), or “an urgency to inform the public about an actual or alleged federal government activity, if made by a person primarily engaged in disseminating information,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(l)(ii).  Requesters seeking expedited processing must submit a statement explaining in detail the basis for the request, and that statement must be certified by the requester to be true and correct.  6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(3). 

Your request for expedited processing is denied because you do not qualify for either category under 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1).  You failed to demonstrate a particular urgency to inform the public about the government activity involved in the request beyond the public’s right to know about government activity generally.  Your letter was conclusory in nature and did not present any facts to justify a grant of expedited processing under the applicable standards. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters. If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #2025-ICFO-25061
communications.communication:
I appeal the agency's blanket b7A assertion on two grounds. 

First, there is no "ongoing law enforcement investigation[]" that could result in a criminal, civil, or administrative proceeding, as required to invoke Exemption 7A. Rather, the investigations ICE performs following an in-custody death -- IHSC Mortality Reviews, Root Cause Analyses, Healthcare and Security Compliance Analyses, and Detainee Death Reviews, pertain solely to "oversight of the performance of duties", rather than an investigation into violations of laws. See, e.g., Jefferson v. DOJ, 284 F.3d 172, 178 (D.C. Cir. 2002). They cannot be fairly characterized, based upon ICE's publicly available policies and procedures and the history of its post-death inspections, to anything constituting an "enforcement proceeding." Consequently, they do not meet Exemption 7A's requirements. Miller v. DOJ, 872 F. Supp. 2d 12, 24-25 (D.D.C. 2012) (explaining that focus is on circumstances of compilation and whether records relate to enforcement proceeding (citing Jefferson 284 F.3d at 176-77)); Rural Hous. All. v. USDA, 498 F.2d 73, 82 (D.C. Cir. 1974) (explaining that purpose of investigatory files is critical factor in establishing law enforcement threshold); Pub. Emps. for Env't Resp. v. U.S. Sec'y. Int'l Boundary & Water Comm'n, 839 F. Supp. 2d 304, 324 (D.D.C. 2012) (explaining that in "assessing whether records were compiled for law enforcement purposes, the 'focus is on how and under what circumstances the requested files were compiled, and whether the files sought relate to anything that can fairly be characterized as an enforcement proceeding'" (quoting Jefferson, 284 F.3d at 176-77)), aff'd in pertinent part & rev'd on other grounds, 740 F.3d 195 (D.C. Cir. 2014).

Second, even if the agency were able to show its allegedly ongoing investigations satisfy the threshold for invoking Exemption 7A, the blanket assertion of the exemption to all potentially responsive records is unlawful and improper. A record-by-record analysis is required to determine whether there is any reasonably segregable, releasable portion of the responsive documents that would not interfere with the ongoing investigation. But ICE did not conduct this analysis. According to the Department of Justice and every court to review agencies’ assertions of the power to engage in blanket 7A withholdings simply because of the existence of an investigation, blanket withholding is unlawful. See, e.g., https://www.justice.gov/oip/page/file/1197166/download at page 11: “While generalized showings of harm are accepted, courts have also cautioned that the exemption [7A] does not permit ‘blanket’ withholding.” See, e.g., Cuban, 744 F. Supp. 2d at 85 (D.D.C. 2010) (stressing that exemption does not permit "blanket" withholding for all records relevant to investigation); UtahAmerica Energy v. U.S. Dep't of Labor, 700 F. Supp. 2d 99, 109 (D.D.C. 2010), rev'd in part, vacated in part sub nom. UtahAmerica Energy, Inc. v. Dep't of Labor, 685 F.3d 1118 (D.C. Cir. 2012) (reiterating that "automatic, or wholesale withholdings" are not authorized simply because law enforcement proceeding is ongoing); United Am. Fin. v. Potter, 531 F. Supp. 2d 29, 3840 (D.D.C. 2008) (reiterating that the agency ‘should be mindful of the standards applicable in this Circuit" and that even under categorical approach, agency must review each document because there is "no 'blanket exemption'"); Gould Inc. v. GSA, 688 F. Supp. 689, 703-04 n.34 (D.D.C. 1988) (describing generic categories approach as steering "middle ground" between detail required by Vaughn Index and blanket withholding).

Please grant expedited processing of this appeal, reverse the decision of the FOIA office, and remand to the agency with instructions to release the record in full. 

Thank you very much, 

Andrew Free

title: Ricardo Carreon Open Record Request

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Ricardo Carreon Open Record Request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am submitting this letter in order to request all documents, public information and public records related to Case ID 24001957, described below.  Please be advised that this request is hereby submitted pursuant to The Texas Open Records Act, Texas Government Code Chapter 552, and The Federal Freedom of Information Act.  I would like to request that all such public information and records be produced as soon as possible.  Please be advised that your agency will be paid the requisite fees, in accordance with the Open Records Act, with respect to your compliance with this request for the production of public records and documents.

Our office represents Ricardo Carreon in regard to injuries he sustained in an accident  on November 22, 2024 at approximately 06:41 AM.  The location of the accident was 2000 57th Street in Temple TX.  The public information and documents which I am requesting at this time (including information that is collected, assembled, or maintained under a law or ordinance or in connection with the transaction of official business by or for a government body, which included the media on which the public information is recorded, paper, film, magnetic, optical, and/or solid state device that can store an electronic signal; tape; computer disk; etc.) are as follows:

•	Any video or photographs taken at the scene of the collision, in the officer’s cruiser, or by responding officers bodycam,

•	Any witness statements, handwritten notes, or supplemental accident report information, 
 

•	An audio copy of the 911 calls from witnesses who called in to report this accident, along with any witness names, addresses, and phone numbers that may be in possession of the communications center, along with any police reports that correspond to this particular incident. 

•	Copies of all sketches, diagrams, witness statements and/or names and phone numbers of witnesses at the scene who did not give statements that may be in the possession of your department.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vic Feazell

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A list of officers within State Transport Police who received an “Unsatisfactory” rating in any category during the Fiscal Year 2024 Employee Performance Management System (EPMS) review process.

For each officer, please include:
Officer name
Rank or title
Troop/region assignment
The category or categories where an “Unsatisfactory” was recorded

If available, any relevant performance metric associated with the rating (e.g. number of inspections completed during the rating period)

I am not requesting any full evaluation forms or narrative comments—only the structured fields as listed above.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA navy military record Michael W McQuillis
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Official Military Personnel File (OMPF) for MICHAEL W. MCQUILLIS  including all Fitness Report and Counseling forms NAVPERS Form 1610/2, Enlisted performance evaluation reports NAVPERS Form 1616-1, the Background Summary (NAVPERS Form 1640/32), Navy Training History NAVPERS form 601-4, Most recent Cumulative Record of Training (NAVPERS Form 5300/16), history of assignments NAVPERS form 601-5 and/or NAVPERS form 1070/605, all military awards and full citations, military education/training courses and Form DD-214. 
Also request Bronze Star Medal and Navy Commendation medal full Citations. Mr MCQUILLIS was a decorated veteran of the Vietnam War with multiple tours of duty.
If necessary please redact any sensitive information protected in accordance with the Privacy Act of 1974.

VETERAN INFORMATION
Name of veteran: Michael W. McQuillis
Branch of service: United States Navy
SSN/SN:   572-66-5973
Rank: Senior Chief Petty Officer 
Navy Rating: BM – Boatswain’s Mate 
Dates of military service: Approximately 1965 - 1986
Date of birth: Approximately 1947
Date of death: November 19, 2009

obituary has been publicly reported https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/name/michael-mcquillis-obituary?pid=168087321

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest . The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Donavan Turner

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: CHARLOTTE MCNAMARA - #2
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

PLEASE PROVIDE ME WITH THE BODY CAMERA FOOTAGE & DASH CAMERA FOOTAGE FOR A TRAFFIC STOP THAT OCCURED ON 08/04/2024 AT APROX 21:22 AT OR NEAR THE LOCATION OF W LAKE SHORE DR & MACARTHUR DR IN WACO, TEXAS INVOLVING CHARLOTTE MCNAMARA A WHITE FEMALE. THIS REQUEST SHOULD COMPLY WITH CHAPTER 1701 OF THE OCCUPATIONS CODE, THANKS.

-B

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Bernadette Feazell

title: FOIA navy record Clayton J. Sweesy

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA navy record Clayton J. Sweesy
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Official Military Personnel File (OMPF) for  CLAYTON JEROME SWEESY   including all Fitness Report and Counseling forms NAVPERS Form 1610/2, Enlisted performance evaluation reports NAVPERS Form 1616-1,  the Background Summary (NAVPERS Form 1640/32), Most recent Cumulative Record of Training (NAVPERS Form 5300/16), history of assignments NAVPERS form 601-5 and/or NAVPERS form 1070/605, all military awards and full citations, military education/training courses and Form DD-214. 
Also request Silver Star Medal, Bronze Star Medal and Navy Commendation medal full Citations. Mr Sweesy was a veteran of the Vietnam War.
If necessary please redact any sensitive information protected in accordance with the Privacy Act of 1974. 

VETERAN INFORMATION

Name of veteran:  Clayton Jerome Sweesy
Branch of service: United States Navy
SSN/SN:   595  24  08
Rank: Chief Petty Officer 
Navy Rating: Equipment Operator EO
Dates of military service:  Approximately  1960 - 1988
Date of birth: Approximately 1942
Date of death:  May 1, 1998

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest . The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Donavan Turner

title: FOIA Navy military record Michael Boynton   Vietnam War

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Navy military record Michael Boynton   Vietnam War
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The Official Military Personnel File (OMPF) for MICHAEL BOYNTON (born 8 Dec 1941)  including all Fitness Report and Counseling forms NAVPERS Form 1610/2, Enlisted performance evaluation reports NAVPERS Form 1616-1,  the Background Summary (NAVPERS Form 1640/32), Most recent Cumulative Record of Training (NAVPERS Form 5300/16), history of assignments form NAVPERS 601-5 and/or NAVPERS Form 1070/605, all military awards and full citations, military education/training courses and Form DD-214. 
Also request Silver Star Medal, Bronze Star Medal and Navy Commendation medal full Citations.
Mr Boynton was a highly decorated United States Navy veteran of the Vietnam War. If necessary please redact any sensitive information protected in accordance with the Privacy Act of 1974. 

VETERAN INFORMATION

Name of veteran:     MICHAEL BOYNTON
Branch of service: United States Navy
SSN/SN:   460-60-0308
Rank: Master Chief Petty Officer E9
Navy Rating: Aviation Ordnanceman AO
Dates of military service:  Approximately  1961 - 1990
Date of birth: December 8, 1941
Date of death:   6 Feb 1998

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest . The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Donavan Turner

title: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request access to the following records related to the arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts, 40 at the time, which occurred on July 30, 2023, at approximately 10:13 PM in the 600 block of Vallotton Dr., Valdosta, GA:

Body-worn camera footage from all officers involved in the traffic stop, physical altercation, and arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts.
Incident report(s) and arrest report(s) related to this case (Report #23-7398).
Dashcam footage from any patrol units that conducted the traffic stop or were involved in the response.
Rear-seat police vehicle footage (if applicable) from the unit that transported Mr. Roberts following his arrest.
This request is focused on essential records that document the escalation of a routine traffic stop into a physical confrontation. If any 911 calls or additional footage (such as surveillance) exist, I request them only if they provide significant additional context to the events.

Fee Waiver Request
I request a fee waiver as the release of these records serves the public interest by providing transparency regarding law enforcement actions and the use of force.

Please provide these records in digital format via email or a secure online portal if available. If any associated fees apply, please inform me before processing. If any portion of this request is denied or redacted, please cite the specific exemption under Georgia law.

Thank you for your time and assistance. Please confirm receipt of this request at your earliest convenience.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

Respectfully,
Tonya Kennedy

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam Footage, Dashcam, and Reports – Arrest of Domanie Chandon Roberts (07/30/2023)
communications.communication:
I have just heard back from State Court about the adjudication status of the case.  I have forwarded the request to the Digital Media Tech and P&E tech to see if they have any photos/videos for this case.

You requested that we notify you before processing if there would be any associated fees.  There will be fees of 50¢ per cd (will not be sent electronically) or between $5-10 for a thumb drive (depending on how much video/photos may be available the information might have to be put on a thumb drive).  You will also incur charges of $12 per hour (1st 15 mins are free) for the copying of any videos/photos and other material being copied/printed.  You requested incident/arrest reports, so that would incur a charge of 10¢ per page, which stands @ 9 pgs or 90¢.  Finally you will have charges for postage between 70¢ and $2.00 (depending on what is being released).

Low end estimate w/ cd(s):
$7.50

High end estimate w/ thumb drive:
$25.00

Please let me know if you would like to continue with the request.

Respectfully,
Tonya Kennedy
Open Records Clerk

500 North Toombs Street

title: Field Interview Cards (Riverside County Sheriff)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Field Interview Cards (Riverside County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am requesting copies of blank field interview cards or equivalent forms filled out during a police stop. Search 2018 to 2024, if there have been no changes since 2018 to the cards, then that year is sufficient. 

Thank you

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

title: Nevada Inmates Wages While Fighting Fires

communications.subject: Nevada Public Records Act Request: Nevada Inmates Wages While Fighting Fires
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Nevada Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1). The number of inmates/offenders from the Nevada Department of Corrections that received training to fight wildfires from January 2019 - December 2024, and the total costs associated with that program. 
2). The wages of Nevada inmates/offenders for that were fighting fires from January 2019-December 2024, including information on race, age, gender and convicted crime but eliminating other private information.
3). The amount of money received into the Division of Forestry Account as outlined in NRS 209.231, reflecting money which is obtained from the operation of a conservation camp and which is not used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses of any conservation camp is required to be deposited in the Division of Forestry Account. 
4). The State Forestry Firewarden's determination of wages that must be paid to inmates/ offenders in the years 2019-2024 in accordance to  NRS 472.040h.
5). The contract between California Division of Forestry and the Nevada Department of Corrections pertaining to financial agreements for use of Nevada's Inmates / Offenders from January 2019-December 2024.
6). All contracts and bills from the Humboldt Conservation Camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" cooperated by a Stor-Al location in Winnemuca as found in Appendix A in https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/Audit/Full/BE2014/Division%20of%20Forestry,%20LA14-01%20Full.pdf

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

michelle baker

communications.subject: Muckrock Request Response
communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Baker,

   Nevada Division of Forestry is in receipt of your public records requests originating on 3/6/25. Below and attached constitutes our response accordingly.


  1.  The number of inmates/offenders from Nevada Department of Corrections that received training to fight wildfires from January 2019-December 2024, and the total costs associated with that program.

Agency Response:  4,509 inmates/offenders were trained by Nevada Division of Forestry during this time period to fight wildfires. NDF does not track the costs associated with this training program specifically so a total cost is not available.


  1.  The wages of Nevada inmates/offender that were fighting fires from January 2019-December 2024, including information on race, age, gender, and convicted crime, but eliminating other private information.

Agency Response: The wage for inmate/offender firefighters regardless of race, age, gender and convicted crime is $1/hr for 24hrs/day while assigned to a fire. NDF does not receive or track any data related to inmate/offender race, age, gender, and convicted crime and therefore cannot produce this information.


  1.  The amount of money received in the Nevada Division of Forestry account as outlined in NRS 209.231, reflecting money which is obtained from the operation of a conservation camp and which is not used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses of any conservation camp is required to be deposited in the Division of Forestry account.

Agency Response: There are no funds received from the operation of conservation camps in excess of those used for salaries, overhead or operating expenses.


  1.  The Forester Firewarden determination of wages that must paid to inmates/offenders in the years 2019-2024 in accordance to NRS 472.040h.

Agency Response: Please see .pdfs attached with determinations and rate sheets.


  1.  The contract between California Division of Forestry and the Nevada Department of Corrections pertaining to financial agreements for use of Nevada's inmates/offenders from January 2019-December 2024.

Agency Response: Nevada Division of Forestry does not track contracts between California Division of Forestry and Nevada Department of Corrections. This request should be re-directed by the requestor to either of those entities.


  1.  All contracts and bills from the Humboldt Conservation Camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" cooperated by a Stor-All location in Winnemucca as found in Appendix A in Division of forestry, LA14-01 full.pdf<https://www.leg.state.nv.us/Division/audit/full/BE2014/Division%20of%20forestry,%20LA14-01%20full.pdf>

Agency Response: Due to the State of Nevada General Records Retention Schedule Version, dated 02/12/2025*, NDF does not have any previous contracts and or billing invoices from the Humboldt Conservation camp regarding the 2011 "general clean up" work performed for Stor-Al Winnemucca location.

This concludes the agency's response to the Muchrock public information request dated 3/6/25.

Sincerely,
Ryan

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Farias-Farias Mortality Review
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Edixon Del Jesus Farias Farias who died in ICE Custody April 18, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrFarias-FariasEdixondelJesus.pdf

I make this request as a member of the media, and therefore seek a fee waiver. Representative edited works based on prior FOIA requests like this one may be reviewed here: https://theappeal.org/authors/andrew-free/; and here: https://atlpresscollective.com/2025/01/31/new-record-sheds-light-on-unreported-death-in-atlanta-airport-customs-inspection/. 

I request expedited processing of this request pursuant to 6 CFR 5.5(e) and attest under penalty of perjury pursuant to 28 USC 1746 that the following statements are true and correct to the best of my knowledge and understanding: 
1. ICE deaths in custody in FY25 are currently on track to equal or surpass the 12 deaths in the previous fiscal year. 

2. IHSC Mortality Reviews provide an authoritative agency accounting of the medical circumstances of in-custody deaths. These reviews often conflict with the public-facing story the agency tells, raising critical questions about accountability, transparency, waste, fraud, and abuse. See https://phr.org/our-work/resources/deadly-failures-preventable-deaths-in-u-s-immigration-detention/.

3. The current administration's expansion of federal immigration detention is the subject of widespread and exceptional media interest in which there exist possible questions about the government's integrity which affect public confidence. See, e.g., 
a. https://www.newyorker.com/news/the-lede/how-many-immigrants-will-die-in-us-custody

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2025-ICFO-25067
communications.communication:
03/13/2025 

Andrew  Free 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR182991 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2025-ICFO-25067 
 
Dear Requester: 

This acknowledges receipt of your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 3/13/2025, your request for a waiver of all assessable FOIA fees, and your request for expedited treatment. Your request was received in this office on 3/13/2025. Specifically, you have requested records pertaining to a copy of the IHSC Mortality Review for Edixon Del Jesus Farias Farias who died in ICE Custody April 18, 2024, according to the Detainee Death Report ICE published: https://www.ice.gov/doclib/foia/reports/ddrFarias-FariasEdixondelJesus.pdf. 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner. 

Your request for expedited treatment is hereby denied. 

Under the DHS FOIA regulations, expedited processing of a FOIA request is warranted if the request involves “circumstances in which the lack of expedited treatment could reasonably be expected to pose an imminent threat to the life or physical safety of an individual,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1)(i), or “an urgency to inform the public about an actual or alleged federal government activity, if made by a person primarily engaged in disseminating information,” 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(l)(ii).  Requesters seeking expedited processing must submit a statement explaining in detail the basis for the request, and that statement must be certified by the requester to be true and correct.  6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(3). 

Your request for expedited processing is denied because you do not qualify for either category under 6 C.F.R. § 5.5(e)(1).  You failed to demonstrate a particular urgency to inform the public about the government activity involved in the request beyond the public’s right to know about government activity generally.  Your letter was conclusory in nature and did not present any facts to justify a grant of expedited processing under the applicable standards. 

After thoroughly reviewing your letter and request for fee waiver, I have determined that you have not presented a convincing argument that you and/or your organization is entitled to a blanket waiver of applicable fees. 

The DHS FOIA Regulations at 6 CFR § 5.11(k)(2) set forth six factors to examine in determining whether the applicable legal standard for a fee waiver has been met.  We will consider these factors in our evaluation of your request for a fee waiver: 

(1) Whether the subject of the requested records concerns “the operations or activities of the government”; 
(2) Whether the disclosure is “likely to contribute” to an understanding of government operations or activities; 
(3) Whether disclosure of the requested information will contribute to the understanding of the public at large, as opposed to the individual understanding of the requestor or a narrow segment of interested persons; 
(4) Whether the contribution to public understanding of government operations or activities will be "significant"; 
(5) Whether the requester has a commercial interest that would be furthered by the requested disclosure; and 
(6) Whether the magnitude of any identified commercial interest to the requestor is sufficiently large in comparison with the public interest in disclosure, that disclosure is primarily in the commercial interest of the requestor. 

As a requester, you bear the burden under FOIA of showing that the fee waiver requirements have been met.  Based on my review of your 3/13/2025 letter and for the reasons stated herein, I have determined that your fee waiver request is deficient because your request did not satisfy factors 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 6. Since your request for a fee waiver has failed to satisfy each of the required factors, I am denying your fee waiver request. 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued. 

If you deem the decision to deny expedited treatment and fee waiver for your request an adverse determination, you have the right to appeal.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(e)(2). You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street,, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

ICE has queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington, at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St, SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-ICFO-25067. Please use this number in future correspondence. 
Sincerely, 

ICE FOIA Office 
Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2024-ICFO-05571
communications.communication:
11/13/2023Brandon GalbraithMuckRock News, DEPT MR154296Boston, Massachusetts 02115RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2024-ICFO-05571        Dear Requester:This acknowledges receipt of your 11/7/2023, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for policy for ICE issued mobile devices.  Your request was received in this office on 11/7/2023.Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner.Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations, as they apply to media requesters.  As a media requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued.We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request.If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison, Fernando Pineiro Jr. at the address above or (866) 633-1182. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.Your request has been assigned reference number 2024-ICFO-05571. Please use this number in future correspondence. Sincerely,ICE FOIA OfficeImmigration and Customs EnforcementFreedom of Information Act Office500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009Washington, D.C. 20536-5009 
This message (including any attachments) contains confidential information intended for a specific individual and purpose, and is protected by law. If you are not the intended recipient, you should delete this message and any disclosure, copying, or distribution
 of this message, or the taking of any action based on it, by you is strictly prohibited. 
Deloitte refers to a Deloitte member firm, one of its related entities, or Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu Limited ("DTTL"). Each Deloitte member firm is a separate legal entity and a member of DTTL. DTTL does not provide services to clients. Please see www.deloitte.com/about
 to learn more.

Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St. SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009.  Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Sincerely, 
Megan Davis 
Deputy FOIA Officer, Operations

title: Request to DoD for all communications with producer Jerry Bruckheimer over last 20 years

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to DoD for all communications with actor/director Jerry Bruckheimer over last 20 years
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All communications between the Department of Defense (DoD) and the Hollywood producer and media executive Jerry Bruckheimer (born Jerome Leon Bruckheimer on September 21, 1943, in Detroit, Michigan), within the 20-year record retention schedule for such records (as specified on p. 202 of the May 2022 DoD document titled "Records Disposition Schedules," Record Group 303). Such communications may include, but should not be limited to, emails, correspondence, memos, and transcriptions of telephone calls.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

title: SPD Discussion on Encryption

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: SPD Discussion on Encryption
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All emails, text messages, and other text-based communications sent between 2020-01-01 and 2020-09-22 to or from any Seattle Police Department staff or contractors that contain the following phrases:

* Tac 9
* Tactical 9
* Tac Nine
* Tactical Nine
* Encrypt
* Encrypted
* Encryption
* 45136

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Nikky Southerland

communications.subject: City of Seattle Public Records Request Center - Invoice Ready :: P064472-092320
communications.communication:
This email is in further response to your public disclosure records request P064472-092320. The Seattle Police Department has records ready to be released pending payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request. 
 SPD strongly encourages online payments during the COVID-19 Pandemic. 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: P064472-092320. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV21-P064472-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. After we receive your payment through the Police Records Request Center Secure Payments, the Public Disclosure Unit will release your records within one to two business days and send you a notice with instructions on how to download the records.
 Please add seattle@mycusthelp.net to your E-mail contacts/address book to ensure delivery of the record center E-mails to your Inbox. (mailto:seattle@mycusthelp.net)

title: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Asheville Police Department)

communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Asheville Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the records listed below regarding the following four software programs: 

• Thompson Reuters Clear (https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/products/clear)
• LexisNexis Accurint (https://www.accurint.com/)
• TransUnion TLOxp, which may also be part of the TruLookup system (https://www.tlo.com/law-enforcement)
• SoundThinking CrimeTracer, which was formerly a product called COPLINK X (https://www.soundthinking.com/law-enforcement/crime-analysis-crimetracer/) from the company formerly known as ShotSpotter

For each of the above mentioned platforms, please provide the following records: 

• CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS —  All contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) and agreements related to the acquisition and use of these "software" programs.
• PURCHASE INFORMATION — All invoices and purchase information for costs and products associated with the above-referenced platforms.

Please provide responsive materials for the period from January 1, 2021 through the date this request is processed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

title: Eric Holcomb Emails

communications.subject: Indiana Access to Public Records Act Request: Eric Holcomb Emails
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Indiana Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I would like to obtain all emails sent to, from, or copied to Eric Holcomb from January 1, 2015 to Present day, containing any of the following non-case-sensitive key-strings: 'EB-5', 'Regional Center', 'USCIS' or 'EB5'.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.


Sincerely,

Taylor Amarel

title: Library Contract Request: Wiley Online Library at Bowie State University

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Library Contract Request: Wiley Online Library at Bowie State University
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

The most recent contract, governing, base, or master license agreement with John Wiley & Sons, Inc. (“Wiley”), relating to the licensing of Wiley Online Library; and
All related terms and conditions, terms of service, amendments, addenda, appendices, attachments, product terms, MOUs, MOAs, data processing agreements, and/or letters of intent; and
All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations with language governing the use of the Wiley Online Library.
Responsive materials include all contracts, agreements, amendments, appendices, invoices, and any other documents listed above that incorporate language governing terms of use of the Wiley Online Library.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

mo

title: Yad Vashem -- NYC Mayor

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Yad Vashem -- NYC Mayor
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

A. Emails containing the non-case sensitive keyword: "Yad Vashem" sent or received by any of the following individuals between March 1, 2022 & May 15, 2022:
   1. Menashe Shapiro 
   2. Fred Kreizman
   3. Mayor Eric Adams
   4. Frank Carone
   5. Dawn Miller

B. The agenda and guest list for the mayor's May 16, 2022 meeting with representatives from Yad Vashem.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Russel Neiss

Welcome to the City of Laredo Open Records Center. We have received your Public Information Request, and it has been diverted to the appropriate department for processing. Pursuant to the Public Information Act, the governmental body will try to complete the request within a reasonable amount of time depending on the nature of the request. However, you can expect to receive notification should the request require more than 10 business days to complete. 

Please note, the Texas Public Information Act does not require a governmental body to create new information, to do legal research, or to answer questions. The request must ask for records or information already in existence. In addition, the City of Laredo may collect a fee as prescribed by law or regulation for the requested documents. If a fee is not prescribed by law or regulation, the fee shall be the actual cost of duplicating the record(s) and any applicable labor costs.

title: Animal Cruelty Evidence Related to PBSO Case #06-25044752

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Animal Cruelty Evidence Related to PBSO Case #06-25044752
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am submitting a formal request for access to and copies of all body worn camera (BWC) and in-car camera (ICC) footage, as well as video and photographic evidence related to the below-detailed incident:
 * Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office (PBSO) Case Number: 06-25044752
 * Nature of Incident: Animal Cruelty
 * Date of Incident/Arrest: March 28, 2025 (arrest date - incident occurred on or about March 19-20, 2025)
 * Time of Arrest: 07:40 hours
 * Location of Arrest: 8559 Boca Rio Rd, Boca Raton, FL 33433
 * Arresting Officer(s): Detective Eric Zadanosky and Deputy Sheriff Derek Harrison (identified from narrative)
 * Defendant: Gabriel Gustavo Martinez, Date of Birth: 08/19/1990
 * Victim: Matthew Avoletta
 * Animal Victim: Gypsy

This request specifically includes, but is not limited to:
1.  All BWC and ICC footage from:
    * Detective Eric Zadanosky
    * Deputy Sheriff Derek Harrison
    * Any other PBSO personnel present at the scene of the arrest, transport, or interaction with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez on March 28, 2025, related to Case #06-25044752.

        * To ensure a comprehensive search, please include footage from:
        * The time of initial contact with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez at 8559 Boca Rio Rd
        * The arrest of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez

        * The transport of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez to the PBSO District 7 substation

        * Any interactions with Gabriel Gustavo Martinez at the substation

        * The transport of Gabriel Gustavo Martinez to West Boca Medical Center

2. Any and all video footage of the alleged animal cruelty incident involving Gabriel Gustavo Martinez and Gypsy, as referenced in the case narrative.

3. All still photographs of Gypsy's injuries, as referenced in the case narrative.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Colon

title: 2018 Crime Incident Records Request (Prince George's County Police Department)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on crime incidents—those classified by your agency as crimes—rather than calls for service or unfounded incidents.
• Year(s) Requested: 2018
• Columns Requested: Incident date, Incident time, Type of crime (e.g., robbery, theft, etc.), Incident ID, and all other available columns that do not require additional processing by the agency or redaction.

If the data are stored in a proprietary or custom electronic format not publicly available, I request that it be converted to a format viewable with standard software, such as Microsoft Excel or CSV. Please avoid providing data in PDF or paper printouts.

This request is made to support academic research conducted in the public interest and is not for commercial purposes. The data will contribute to a research project assessing the effect of music concerts on crime, aiming to enhance public understanding of how large events influence community safety.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

title: FBI support for 2022 documentary "The Thief Collector"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI support for 2022 documentary "The Thief Collector"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to FBI support for or collaboration with the production of the 2022 documentary film "The Thief Collector," directed by Allison Otto. Such documents may include, but are not limited to, script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of the FBI and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "The Thief Collector," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication. I request a search of all locations where such documents might be located, including but not limited to the entertainment liaison offices and communications HQ or similar offices.

Attached is a document, released to me by the FBI in response to a previous FOIA request, confirming that the FBI supported the production of "The Thief Collector."

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1634798-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request

If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-0] please enter [1195846-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-1] please enter [1195846-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000
Case Type:
FOIPA
Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)

The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.

You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.


Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system, and the FBI receives a voluminous amount of requests on a daily, weekly, monthly, and annual basis.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Our complex requests are further divided into small (51-250 pages), medium (251-500 pages), large (501-4,999), and extra-large (over 5,000 pages) sub-tracks.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  The more potentially responsive pages a request has, the more complex it becomes, greatly increasing the time required for processing. Generally, the larger the file, the longer it takes to process.
Currently, simple track cases average approximately 230 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Complex requests in the small processing track are currently averaging 1,085 days from the date of receipt for processing, those in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,310 days, those in the large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and those in the extra-large track are averaging 2,370 days  .


Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

title: FBI support for History Channel TV series "America's Book of Secrets"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI support for History Channel TV series "America's Book of Secrets"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to FBI support for or collaboration with the production of any episodes of the fourth season (2021) of the History Channel TV series "America's Book of Secrets." Such documents may include, but are not limited to, script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of the FBI and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "America's Book of Secrets," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication. I request a search of all locations where such documents might be located, including but not limited to the entertainment liaison offices and communications HQ or similar offices.

Attached is a document, released to me by the FBI in response to a previous FOIA request, confirming that the FBI supported the production of "America's Book of Secrets." Given that only the fourth season of the show was produced during the period for which the aforementioned document pertains (2019-2023), the FBI must have supported one or more episodes from the fourth season (2021).

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo
